The article discusses the progress made by the My Brother's Keeper (MBK) initiative in the past two years. The MBK initiative was established to address opportunity gaps faced by boys and young men of color and ensure that all young people can reach their full potential. Since its inception, nearly 250 communities in all 50 states have accepted the MBK Community Challenge, and over $600 million in private sector and philanthropic grants have been committed. The article highlights various initiatives and commitments made by federal agencies, state and local communities, and the private sector to support the goals of MBK, such as mentoring programs, summer job opportunities, and educational reforms. The article also announces new commitments and initiatives that aim to expand opportunities in STEM education and entrepreneurship for underrepresented minorities. Overall, the article emphasizes the progress and achievements made by MBK in expanding opportunities and creating pathways for success for young people.